<p188:cmLst xmlns:a="http://schemas.openxmlformats.org/drawingml/2006/main" xmlns:r="http://schemas.openxmlformats.org/officeDocument/2006/relationships" xmlns:p188="http://schemas.microsoft.com/office/powerpoint/2018/8/main"><p188:cm id="{E6164436-D318-4A35-9139-7BB944AE88E7}" authorId="{B0A0341B-4108-E3C8-F18D-10AB4476D472}" created="2026-03-24T19:34:45.171"><ac:txMkLst xmlns:ac="http://schemas.microsoft.com/office/drawing/2013/main/command"><pc:docMk xmlns:pc="http://schemas.microsoft.com/office/powerpoint/2013/main/command"/><pc:sldMk xmlns:pc="http://schemas.microsoft.com/office/powerpoint/2013/main/command" cId="382456698" sldId="382"/><ac:spMk id="40" creationId="{6F89CFA7-6962-7603-8169-215209443C90}"/><ac:txMk cp="156" len="39"><ac:context len="196" hash="4088707988"/></ac:txMk></ac:txMkLst><p188:pos x="1617031" y="1191244"/><p188:replyLst><p188:reply id="{193076BE-1975-4236-92B2-0A40A6F94CCB}" authorId="{3881937D-687C-8E2F-43B2-047B57AA50D8}" created="2026-03-27T19:46:58.862"><p188:txBody><a:bodyPr/><a:lstStyle/><a:p><a:r><a:rPr lang="en-US"/><a:t>Moved the comment about tour inequality to the painpoints section, though I'm not sure it is important enough to include. I think you would want better prospects going to better sales people</a:t></a:r></a:p></p188:txBody></p188:reply></p188:replyLst><p188:txBody><a:bodyPr/><a:lstStyle/><a:p><a:r><a:rPr lang="en-US"/><a:t>This seems like a pain point not something that should be in this descriptor section?</a:t></a:r></a:p></p188:txBody></p188:cm><p188:cm id="{7E635A12-38CF-4F19-9E81-8240693185E9}" authorId="{B0A0341B-4108-E3C8-F18D-10AB4476D472}" created="2026-03-24T19:37:36.743"><ac:txMkLst xmlns:ac="http://schemas.microsoft.com/office/drawing/2013/main/command"><pc:docMk xmlns:pc="http://schemas.microsoft.com/office/powerpoint/2013/main/command"/><pc:sldMk xmlns:pc="http://schemas.microsoft.com/office/powerpoint/2013/main/command" cId="382456698" sldId="382"/><ac:spMk id="6" creationId="{2F7C3EF4-7AF3-F73E-01D3-839AB5E95D3C}"/><ac:txMk cp="357" len="57"><ac:context len="525" hash="3020886346"/></ac:txMk></ac:txMkLst><p188:pos x="5296717" y="1286940"/><p188:replyLst><p188:reply id="{D3EF86CA-6C0F-4967-909C-C16507A0E6C2}" authorId="{3881937D-687C-8E2F-43B2-047B57AA50D8}" created="2026-03-27T19:52:15.412"><p188:txBody><a:bodyPr/><a:lstStyle/><a:p><a:r><a:rPr lang="en-US"/><a:t>I think this was more about SE’s ability to sell being reliant on telemarketing and marketing efforts upstream</a:t></a:r></a:p></p188:txBody></p188:reply></p188:replyLst><p188:txBody><a:bodyPr/><a:lstStyle/><a:p><a:r><a:rPr lang="en-US"/><a:t>I am not understanding the pain point here, are we trying to say that it’s hard to ensure attendance at the presentations, which impacts sales?</a:t></a:r></a:p></p188:txBody></p188:cm><p188:cm id="{495A7F6C-0B99-436C-A67D-B2E6B051C831}" authorId="{B0A0341B-4108-E3C8-F18D-10AB4476D472}" created="2026-03-24T19:42:41.839"><ac:txMkLst xmlns:ac="http://schemas.microsoft.com/office/drawing/2013/main/command"><pc:docMk xmlns:pc="http://schemas.microsoft.com/office/powerpoint/2013/main/command"/><pc:sldMk xmlns:pc="http://schemas.microsoft.com/office/powerpoint/2013/main/command" cId="382456698" sldId="382"/><ac:spMk id="40" creationId="{6F89CFA7-6962-7603-8169-215209443C90}"/><ac:txMk cp="116" len="39"><ac:context len="156" hash="1946533892"/></ac:txMk></ac:txMkLst><p188:pos x="1886997" y="921278"/><p188:txBody><a:bodyPr/><a:lstStyle/><a:p><a:r><a:rPr lang="en-US"/><a:t>Need to confirm with kelly - I think VIP reps come at the end and this should be removed</a:t></a:r></a:p></p188:txBody></p188:cm><p188:cm id="{EED77D14-D0D9-6D4A-A432-E7E2EB40F509}" authorId="{084F02DE-1BEA-55CD-55ED-B0569F4DBDCD}" created="2026-04-09T21:57:09.393"><ac:deMkLst xmlns:ac="http://schemas.microsoft.com/office/drawing/2013/main/command"><pc:docMk xmlns:pc="http://schemas.microsoft.com/office/powerpoint/2013/main/command"/><pc:sldMk xmlns:pc="http://schemas.microsoft.com/office/powerpoint/2013/main/command" cId="382456698" sldId="382"/><ac:spMk id="37" creationId="{0BD6177C-0C8B-2247-0F47-7EDB4EC25FD2}"/></ac:deMkLst><p188:replyLst><p188:reply id="{85C11E38-3F54-3446-ACCE-101272450112}" authorId="{084F02DE-1BEA-55CD-55ED-B0569F4DBDCD}" created="2026-04-09T22:05:48.568"><p188:txBody><a:bodyPr/><a:lstStyle/><a:p><a:r><a:rPr lang="en-US"/><a:t>Tour Arrival and Assignment i mean - the bullet beneath tour arrival says assign</a:t></a:r></a:p></p188:txBody></p188:reply></p188:replyLst><p188:txBody><a:bodyPr/><a:lstStyle/><a:p><a:r><a:rPr lang="en-US"/><a:t>is this the same step?</a:t></a:r></a:p></p188:txBody></p188:cm><p188:cm id="{8323F166-05A0-824C-9742-B9DD901F983F}" authorId="{084F02DE-1BEA-55CD-55ED-B0569F4DBDCD}" created="2026-04-09T21:59:22.846"><ac:txMkLst xmlns:ac="http://schemas.microsoft.com/office/drawing/2013/main/command"><pc:docMk xmlns:pc="http://schemas.microsoft.com/office/powerpoint/2013/main/command"/><pc:sldMk xmlns:pc="http://schemas.microsoft.com/office/powerpoint/2013/main/command" cId="382456698" sldId="382"/><ac:spMk id="6" creationId="{2F7C3EF4-7AF3-F73E-01D3-839AB5E95D3C}"/><ac:txMk cp="25" len="204"><ac:context len="525" hash="3020886346"/></ac:txMk></ac:txMkLst><p188:pos x="9460131" y="435650"/><p188:replyLst><p188:reply id="{2D27619E-AB7A-CC40-BE97-D8E3FBCA876D}" authorId="{084F02DE-1BEA-55CD-55ED-B0569F4DBDCD}" created="2026-04-09T22:00:35.788"><p188:txBody><a:bodyPr/><a:lstStyle/><a:p><a:r><a:rPr lang="en-US"/><a:t>perhaps change it to.. tour quality varies significantly, requiring sales reps to spend a disproportionate amount of time with low conversion-potential candidates. (i.e.,  its a time suck)</a:t></a:r></a:p></p188:txBody></p188:reply></p188:replyLst><p188:txBody><a:bodyPr/><a:lstStyle/><a:p><a:r><a:rPr lang="en-US"/><a:t>interestingly, if you look at the stats, the better sales reps have higher conversion of all types of lead quality.  would rethink the framing of this as it could be easily spun that perhaps the issue is the sales rep and not the lead</a:t></a:r></a:p></p188:txBody></p188:cm><p188:cm id="{7614FB72-FB60-9748-96AF-F8E5122E82A9}" authorId="{084F02DE-1BEA-55CD-55ED-B0569F4DBDCD}" created="2026-04-09T22:04:28.040"><ac:txMkLst xmlns:ac="http://schemas.microsoft.com/office/drawing/2013/main/command"><pc:docMk xmlns:pc="http://schemas.microsoft.com/office/powerpoint/2013/main/command"/><pc:sldMk xmlns:pc="http://schemas.microsoft.com/office/powerpoint/2013/main/command" cId="382456698" sldId="382"/><ac:spMk id="6" creationId="{2F7C3EF4-7AF3-F73E-01D3-839AB5E95D3C}"/><ac:txMk cp="337" len="187"><ac:context len="525" hash="3020886346"/></ac:txMk></ac:txMkLst><p188:pos x="9703199" y="1089620"/><p188:replyLst><p188:reply id="{A6550A7D-0417-5C42-8661-3DC1DD6A6187}" authorId="{084F02DE-1BEA-55CD-55ED-B0569F4DBDCD}" created="2026-04-09T22:04:52.825"><p188:txBody><a:bodyPr/><a:lstStyle/><a:p><a:r><a:rPr lang="en-US"/><a:t>also curious if you guys noticed any patterns in regional pay/comp - were some regions SEs making more? that could be an interesting insight</a:t></a:r></a:p></p188:txBody></p188:reply><p188:reply id="{063BC607-9F7E-9A4C-B5D9-C0D631FC4387}" authorId="{084F02DE-1BEA-55CD-55ED-B0569F4DBDCD}" created="2026-04-09T22:06:48.803"><p188:txBody><a:bodyPr/><a:lstStyle/><a:p><a:r><a:rPr lang="en-US"/><a:t>are there any issues in rescission? </a:t></a:r></a:p></p188:txBody></p188:reply></p188:replyLst><p188:txBody><a:bodyPr/><a:lstStyle/><a:p><a:r><a:rPr lang="en-US"/><a:t>this doesnt really make any sense. youre just saying tour volume is dependent on sales and telemarketing which is obvious and stated before these steps. could reframe to: no shows can impact conversion rates and comp potential 

or consider some other core issues in sales assignment are the 1) manual allocation and lack of governance on tour planning/scheduling limits optimization of reps, 2) the bias of scheduling good reps better dates / times which can hurt newer or learning reps, 3) site-dependent tour planning / scheduling makes it difficult to understand success patterns and repeat/standardize across brands, 4) limited data and analytics is used to do tour planning (e.g., forecasting potential, etc.) 5) rep performance and KPIs are not standardized</a:t></a:r></a:p></p188:txBody></p188:cm></p188:cmLst>